{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WwrTvLYk8BpWctREt7V4kj","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→#' @title Set unit of a single forecast manually\n     2→#'\n     3→#' @description\n     4→#' Helper function to set the unit of a single forecast (i.e. the\n     5→#' combination of columns that uniquely define a single forecast) manually.\n     6→#' This simple function keeps the columns specified in `forecast_unit` (plus\n     7→#' additional protected columns, e.g. for observed values, predictions or\n     8→#' quantile levels) and removes duplicate rows. `set_forecast_unit()` will\n     9→#' mainly be called when constructing a `forecast` object\n    10→#' via the `forecast_unit` argument in `as_forecast_<type>`.\n    11→#'\n    12→#' If not done explicitly, `scoringutils` attempts to determine the unit\n    13→#' of a single forecast automatically by simply assuming that all column names\n    14→#' are relevant to determine the forecast unit. This may lead to unexpected\n    15→#' behaviour, so setting the forecast unit explicitly can help make the code\n    16→#' easier to debug and easier to read.\n    17→#'\n    18→#' @inheritParams as_forecast_doc_template\n    19→#' @param forecast_unit Character vector with the names of the columns that\n    20→#'   uniquely identify a single forecast.\n    21→#' @importFrom cli cli_warn\n    22→#' @returns A data.table with only those columns kept that are relevant to\n    23→#'   scoring or denote the unit of a single forecast as specified by the user.\n    24→#' @importFrom data.table ':=' is.data.table copy\n    25→#' @importFrom checkmate assert_character assert_subset\n    26→#' @keywords as_forecast\n    27→#' @examples\n    28→#' example_quantile |>\n    29→#'   scoringutils:::set_forecast_unit(\n    30→#'     c(\"location\", \"target_end_date\", \"target_type\", \"horizon\", \"model\")\n    31→#'   )\n    32→set_forecast_unit <- function(data, forecast_unit) {\n    33→  data <- ensure_data.table(data)\n    34→  assert_subset(forecast_unit, names(data), empty.ok = FALSE)\n    35→  keep_cols <- c(get_protected_columns(data), forecast_unit)\n    36→  out <- unique(data[, .SD, .SDcols = keep_cols])\n    37→  return(out)\n    38→}\n    39→\n    40→\n    41→#' @title Get unit of a single forecast\n    42→#' @description\n    43→#' Helper function to get the unit of a single forecast, i.e.\n    44→#' the column names that define where a single forecast was made for.\n    45→#' This just takes all columns that are available in the data and subtracts\n    46→#' the columns that are protected, i.e. those returned by\n    47→#' [get_protected_columns()] as well as the names of the metrics that were\n    48→#' specified during scoring, if any.\n    49→#' @inheritParams as_forecast_doc_template\n    50→#' @inheritSection forecast_types Forecast unit\n    51→#' @return\n    52→#' A character vector with the column names that define the unit of\n    53→#' a single forecast\n    54→#' @importFrom checkmate assert_data_frame\n    55→#' @export\n    56→#' @keywords diagnose-inputs\n    57→get_forecast_unit <- function(data) {\n    58→  assert_data_frame(data)\n    59→  protected_columns <- get_protected_columns(data)\n    60→  protected_columns <- c(protected_columns, attr(data, \"metrics\"))\n    61→  forecast_unit <- setdiff(colnames(data), unique(protected_columns))\n    62→  return(forecast_unit)\n    63→}\n    64→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_013XjpkUBX4qoFd324ALdvyt","session_id":"85af7904-8b76-495a-a761-ec1bec0c63a6","uuid":"4b4f6966-476f-4644-a6c6-a38a6cddf441"}
